\boxed{B}
The correct answer is **B** because although ethnicity correlates with disparities in cancer outcomes and access to care (which can indirectly influence where patients receive treatment or pass away), there is no direct medical evidence linking ethnicity to specific geographic patterns of where cancer-related deaths occur. The retrieved documents emphasize mortality rate differences and unequal access to palliative services, not variations in physical location of death. Thus, ethnicity does not directly affect where people with cancer die—rather, it influences the circumstances surrounding end-of-life care through social determinants.
\boxed{B}

